# PCONFIG (Peripheral Configuration Library) Configuration

menuconfig PCONFIG
	bool "PCONFIG (Peripheral Configuration Library)"
	default n
	depends on OSAL && HAL
	help
	  Peripheral Configuration Library provides device-tree-like hardware
	  configuration management.

	  PCONFIG acts as a hardware abstraction layer that describes the physical
	  hardware configuration of a platform (board variant, peripheral
	  connections, pin mappings, etc.) in a structured, data-driven way.

	  Key features:
	  - Platform-specific hardware descriptions
	  - Board variant management (e.g., H200_100P_V1, H200_100P_V2)
	  - Peripheral configuration tables
	  - Runtime hardware detection and configuration

	  Memory footprint: ~10KB code + configuration data (varies by platform)

	  Use cases:
	  - Multi-board product variants
	  - Hardware abstraction for applications
	  - Runtime board identification
	  - Peripheral auto-configuration

	  Dependencies: OSAL (for basic services), HAL (for hardware access)

	  Note: Enable OSAL, HAL, and TYPES first in "Core Modules" menu.

	  Recommended: Enable for products with multiple hardware variants

	  If unsure, say Y.

if PCONFIG

menu "PCONFIG Build Configuration"

config PCONFIG_BUILD_STATIC
	bool "Build static library (.a)"
	default n
	help
	  Build PCONFIG as a static library (libpconfig.a).

	  Static linking advantages:
	  - No runtime dependencies
	  - Configuration data embedded in executable
	  - Slightly faster (no dynamic linking)

	  Recommended: Enable for embedded systems with fixed hardware

config PCONFIG_BUILD_SHARED
	bool "Build shared library (.so)"
	default n
	help
	  Build PCONFIG as a shared library (libpconfig.so).

	  Shared library advantages:
	  - Can update hardware configurations without recompiling apps
	  - Smaller executable size
	  - Code sharing between processes

	  Use cases:
	  - Systems with multiple applications using PCONFIG
	  - Field-updatable hardware configurations

	  Recommended: Enable for multi-application systems

endmenu

endif # PCONFIG
